eeding advocates alongside celebrities such as Beyoncé, Serena Williams, and Michelle Obama-that are not rooted in loss. Through cultural critique and in-depth interviews, Nash acknowledges the complexities of Black motherhood outside its use as political currency. Throughout, Nash imagines a Black feminist project that refuses the lure of locating the precarity of Black life in women and instead invites readers to theorize, organize, and dream into being new modes of Black motherhood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAfrican American mothers. 0aAfrican American womenxMedical carezUnited States. 0aBlack lives matter movement. 0aDoulaszUnited States. 0aRace discriminationxHealth aspectszUnited States. 0aReproductive health servicesxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aWomanism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074331940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478021728zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478021728423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478021728/original  a978-3-11-074331-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles